# *java.time* 

The `java.util` Date-Time API and their formatting API, `SimpleDateFormat` are outdated and error-prone. It is recommended to stop using them completely and switch to the [modern Date-Time API](https://www.oracle.com/technical-resources/articles/java/jf14-Date-Time.html)&lt;sup&gt;*&lt;/sup&gt;.


**Solution using `java.time`, the modern Date-Time API:** You can specify multiple optional patterns using square brackets inside a `DateTimeFormatter`. Parse the date strings into `LocalDate` and compare them using [`LocalDate#isBefore`](https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/api/java/time/LocalDate.html#isBefore-java.time.chrono.ChronoLocalDate-), `LocalDate#isAfter`, `LocalDate#isEqual` etc.

**Demo:**

